  "prompt": "Does money laundering fall under criminal legislation?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a criminal offense under both domestic and international legal frameworks. It involves the process of making illegally obtained money (from activities like drug trafficking, fraud, corruption, or organized crime) appear legitimate by disguising its origins. This is achieved through a series of transactions designed to obscure the source of the funds.\n\n### Criminal Legislation on Money Laundering:\n1. **International Frameworks**:\n   - The **United Nations Convention against Illicit Traffic in Narcotic Drugs and Psychotropic Substances (1988)** was one of the first international treaties to address money laundering.\n   - The **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, an intergovernmental organization, sets global standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\n2. **Domestic Laws**:\n   - Most countries have specific legislation criminalizing money laundering. For example:\n     - In the **United States**, the **Bank Secrecy Act (1970)** and the **USA PATRIOT Act (2001)** are key laws targeting money laundering.\n     - In the **United Kingdom**, the **Proceeds of Crime Act 2002** criminalizes money laundering.\n     - In **India**, the **Prevention of Money Laundering Act (PMLA), 2002** addresses this crime.\n\n3. **Penalties**:\n   - Penalties for money laundering vary by jurisdiction but typically include substantial fines, imprisonment, and asset forfeiture.\n\n### Why Money Laundering is Criminalized:\nMoney laundering facilitates and perpetuates serious crimes by enabling criminals to enjoy the profits of their illegal activities. It also undermines the integrity of financial systems and can have significant economic and social consequences. As such, it is treated as a serious criminal offense worldwide.",
